<article>
    <h1>Poly&#xAD;tech&#xAD;nic: Free&#xAD;dom and re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;si&#xAD;bil&#xAD;ity in a hands-on en&#xAD;vi&#xAD;ron&#xAD;ment</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210111/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-11"><time>2021-01-11</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | SMART PARENTING</span>
        - <span role="byline">Elisa Chia elisac@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>If you think study­ing at a poly­tech­nic is more re­laxed than at a ju­nior col­lege, Ms Anita Kuan wants you to think again.</p>
    <p>The Te­masek Poly­tech­nic deputy prin­ci­pal says this is a com­mon mis­con­cep­tion. “Ask any poly­tech­nic stu­dent and he or she would say it’s not true.”</p>
    <p>She adds: “Ev­ery set of re­sults – from six semesters al­to­gether – will count to­wards the fi­nal GPA (grade point av­er­age).</p>
    <p>“So if you’re think­ing that you can chill at the be­gin­ning and then ‘chiong’ (Hokkien for rush) at the end, sorry, this is not go­ing to work in your favour.”</p>
    <p>One of the most ob­vi­ous dif­fer­ences be­tween poly­tech­nic and ju­nior col­lege life is “no school uni­form”, she says with a laugh.</p>
    <p>And that al­ways comes up tops when she asks teenagers what is the best thing about be­ing in a poly­tech­nic.</p>
    <p>“I sup­pose in some ways, it’s about free­dom. What do I wear to­day? What choices do I make? What elec­tive pro­grammes do I take?” says Ms Kuan, for­merly a lec­turer and se­nior di­rec­tor at Ngee Ann Poly­tech­nic for more than two decades.</p>
    <p>The poly­tech­nic route suits those who en­joy tin­ker­ing with ideas and learn­ing by do­ing. But do not dis­miss the hands-on pro­jects as “masak-masak” (Malay col­lo­qui­al­ism for play­ing around), she says.</p>
    <p>“When you cre­ate solutions and work on pro­jects, they ac­tu­ally go out to the in­dus­try part­ners who will then come back and give you feed­back on how you’ve done. There is a real con­nec­tion be­tween the­ory and prac­ti­cal.”</p>
    <p>Stu­dents should find out more about the poly­tech­nic and ju­nior col­lege routes at the start of sec­ondary school, not after the O-level ex­am­i­na­tions.</p>
    <p>“Visit open houses and speak to friends who have gone through the jour­ney ahead of you, so you get a sense of what it is like,” she sug­gests. “And I’d say, it’s use­ful to speak to peo­ple who know you and your learn­ing style bet­ter than your­self.”</p>
    <p>With the “free­dom” that comes with be­ing a poly­tech­nic stu­dent, one is ex­pected to be dis­ci­plined, she adds. “You don’t have any­one breath­ing down your neck say­ing, ‘If you don’t sub­mit this, I’d call your mother.’ You have to be re­ally re­spon­si­ble.”</p>
    <p>Some peo­ple fear that if they choose the poly­tech­nic route, they can­not go on to univer­sity.</p>
    <p>Ms Kuan says this is an­other mis­con­cep­tion. There are many path­ways to a univer­sity ed­u­ca­tion nowa­days, with some grad­u­ates pre­fer­ring to gain work­ing ex­pe­ri­ence first be­fore con­tin­u­ing with ed­u­ca­tion.</p>
    <p>“The beauty of a poly­tech­nic ed­u­ca­tion is re­ally, at the end of your three years, you can ac­tu­ally work if you want to,” she says.</p>
    <p>It is im­por­tant to have a con­tin­u­ing growth mind­set.</p>
    <p>She adds: “It’s about hav­ing to re­fresh your skills be­cause the world is chang­ing so quickly.”</p>
    <p>The beauty of a poly­tech­nic ed­u­ca­tion is re­ally, at the end of your three years, you can ac­tu­ally work if you want to.</p>
    <p>MS ANITA KUAN (above), deputy prin­ci­pal of Te­masek Poly­tech­nic</p>
    <p>For more sto­ries on how to help your child suc­ceed in school and life, go to the Smart Par­ent­ing mi­crosite at str.sg/smart­par­ent­ing</p>

